Sure, if you can attach the solution file which can save our time.

The short answer is, what you're doing is fine, you don't need to mess with Argument.

The long answer is what you put in the Input class will get converted by the Mutation's meta class:
https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene/blob/master/graphene/types/mutation.py

From there, the attributes defined on Input are passed to Field as args=:
https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene/blob/master/graphene/types/field.py

Field __init__ then calls to_argument(args), which runs them through a few conditions of interest to you:
```

        if isinstance(arg, Dynamic):
            arg = arg.get_type()
            if arg is None:
                # If the Dynamic type returned None
                # then we skip the Argument
                continue

        if isinstance(arg, UnmountedType):
            arg = arg.Argument()

        if not isinstance(arg, Argument):
            raise ValueError('Unknown argument "{}".'.format(default_name))

```

So as you can see, it handles Dynamic types, UnmountedType (this is what you're using), and Argument types.

Btw, if you mean to use this for Relay, then you can use the ClientIDMutation parent:

class AMutation(graphene.relay.ClientIDMutation):
    class Input:
        foo = graphene.String()
        bar = graphene.String()

    ok = graphene.Boolean()

    @classmethod
    def mutate_and_get_payload(cls, input, context, info):
        ok = True
        return AMutation(ok=ok)

