@JulianSchneider 

I haven't tried it myself, but yes, I would like to think you could subclass `DjangoObjectType` to add all properties. I would still encourage you *not* to as it is potentially dangerous when someone else comes along and adds a `@property` to a model, unknowingly exposing new data to the graphql endpoint.

If you primary use is to add a global property that is shared by all of your models, then I think the easiest and most future-proof solution would be to add a "mixin" to your objects. Something like this:

```

class EncryptedIdMixin(object):
    encrypted_id = graphene.String()

...

class MyObject(EncryptedIdMixin, DjangoObjectType):

    class Meta:
        ...
```

If that's the case, then there's a bug I've encountered. Given this query:

```
{
    player {
        games {
            ...
        }
    }
}
```

This schema works without error:

```
class Game(ObjectType):
    ...

class Player(ObjectType):
    games = List(Game, recent_count=Int(default_value=0))
```

But this does not (the default is 1, not None):

```
class Game(ObjectType):
    ...

class Player(ObjectType):
    games = List(Game, recent_count=Int(default_value=None))
    def resolve_games(root, info, recent_count):
        ...
```

Even though both of the schemas provide a default value, only the latter actually *uses* the default value; the latter fails with `resolve_games() missing 1 required positional argument: 'recent_count'`

HOWEVER:

When I change resolve_games to this:

```
def resolve_games(root, info, recent_count=None):  # Added a default to the function
```

The query works without arguments. It should be made clear that GraphQL *does* support queries without arguments, or with optional arguments, but implementing that in the schema requires modifying the resolver function, not the class field.

I wanted to go with your suggested method, but after I tried implementing it it has a side effect. If a bool value isn't passed it assumes it's set to false. This could cause problems when a method has an argument that defaults to true. 

    python -m escpos.cli set --no-flip
    {'invert': False, 'smooth': False, 'flip': False}

    python -m escpos.cli set --flip
    {'invert': False, 'smooth': False, 'flip': True}


If it's called from python, it would default to true, but from the CLI it would default to false. I think fca3631 is the better way to go since it only send true or false if the user explicitly passes the argument. This preserves the method's default values.

Untested code, but this should be the implementation of the non-copy approach:
```C++
auto v = new std::vector<int>(some_func());
auto capsule = py::capsule(v, [](void *v) { delete reinterpret_cast<std::vector<int>>(v); }
return py::array(v->size(), v->data(), capsule);
```
Yes, probably more black magic than you might expect. But then again, you're not doing something simple either. You are keeping a C++ object alive to make sure you can access its internal data safely, without leaking the memory.

But if you don't mind the copy, just go:
```C++
auto v = some_func();
return py::array(v.size(), v.data());
```

